  "text": "It is further worth considering that two areas of great recent interest in AMDFthe complement system and anti-VEGF therapyFare likely to modulate the function of circulating leucocytes in AMD. For example, anaphylotoxins generated during the formation of complement complexes have a number of bioactive effects on leucocytes, including increased migration and synthesis of pro-inflammatory mediators. [CITATION_1] It is also interesting, in light of the success of anti-VEGF therapies in the management of neovascular AMD, that VEGF itself increases expression of endothelial cell adhesion molecules and elevates recruitment of macrophages and neutrophils under some conditions, in addition to its well-appreciated direct effects on vascular growth. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] How might macrophages protect against macular degeneration?",
